'''Susan S. Bernecker''' (born March 26, 1955) is a former [[U.S. Republican Party|Republican]] candidate for the [[Jefferson Parish, Louisiana|Jefferson Parish]] City Council in [[suburban]] [[New Orleans]]. She was defeated 33% to 58% by Nick Giambelluca, [[nephew]] of the Jefferson Parish election supervisor, Tony Giambelluca.
{{Quotation|"The night of the election the numbers came in for everybody but me for an hour and a half. When my numbers didnâ€™t come in everyone in my party went wild".|Susan Bernecker}}
After her loss and under the protection of state law to inspect the [[voting machine]]s, Bernecker went to the [[warehouse]] where the [[Sequoia Pacific]] computers had been taken. There a producer [[videotape]]d Bernecker as she pressed the button next to her name on the [[ballot]] which registered the name of her opponent on a [[LED]] screen. Bernecker checked twelve machines and her name appeared displayed only a third of the time.<ref>[http://www.votefraud.org/relevance_o'halloran_pandora's_box.htm VoteFraud.org]</ref>
Bernecker was a participant in the [[Hursti Hack]] held in [[Tallahassee, Florida|Tallahassee]], [[Florida]], and featured in [[Hacking Democracy]], an [[HBO]] [[Documentary film|documentary]] on the errors of the [[Premier Election Solutions|Diebold Election Systems]] Accu-Vote OS 1.94w (optical scan) voting machine.<ref>[http://www.hbo.com/docs/programs/hackingdemocracy/synopsis.html "Hacking Democracy," HBO documentary. Retrieved October 16, 2006]</ref> ==References== {{Reflist}}
